# Security

## Non-negotiables

- **Never log PII**: emails, full names, addresses, NI numbers, payment details. Pino redacts; Sentry scrubs.
- **Never put secrets in client bundle**: `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` only for safe values; everything else server-only.
- **Always verify webhook signatures** before processing. Read raw body first.
- **RLS on every domain table**. CI fails if an INSERT migration omits RLS.
- **Validate every input**: Zod on Route Handlers; client-side too.
- **Cookies**: `Secure + HttpOnly + SameSite=Lax`.
- **CSRF**: same-origin checks + custom header on mutating fetches.
- **CSP**: strict, defined in `next.config.ts`.

## OWASP Top 10 reminders

A01 Access — RLS + layout-level membership re-check + tests.
A02 Crypto — TLS, encrypted at rest, password hashing handled by Supabase.
A03 Injection — parameterised queries via Supabase JS, Zod validation.
A04 Insecure design — read flow doc + threat model first.
A05 Misconfig — security headers, private storage buckets by default.
A06 Vulnerable deps — Renovate + `pnpm audit` in CI.
A07 Auth — Supabase Auth, MFA optional MVP.
A08 Integrity — webhook sig + audit log.
A09 Logging — Sentry + Axiom + alerts.
A10 SSRF — no user-supplied URLs fetched server-side without allowlist.

See `docs/10-security/owasp-checklist.md`.

## PII fields

These columns + buckets contain PII / sensitive data:

- `profiles.contact_email`, `contact_phone`, `address`, `full_name`.
- `auth.users.email`.
- `compliance_documents` storage paths (esp. RTR identity docs).
- `messages.body`.
- `tickets.description`.

Never log these. Mask in error messages. Scrub before sending to Sentry.

## Secret handling

- Production secrets only in Vercel / GitHub Environments / Supabase secrets store.
- Never in code, commits, Slack, screenshots.
- Rotate quarterly per `docs/10-security/secrets-management.md`.

## When you see something suspicious

Stop, ask. A slightly-wrong security control beats a broken one.
